# 1. Purpose

This document defines the backend architecture of the Halisako platform.

It serves as the engineering contract for implementing the backend and establishes the architectural principles that every future service must follow.

This document covers:

- Backend Architecture
- Domain Boundaries
- API Standards
- Authentication
- Database Design
- Upload Pipeline
- Job Orchestration
- Experience Generation Pipeline
- HXT Lifecycle
- Deployment Architecture
- Scalability Strategy

---

# 2. Vision

Halisako is not a single AI application.

It is a platform for transforming structured human inputs into expressive digital experiences.

The backend therefore must:

- support multiple products
- remain product-agnostic
- isolate product logic
- centralize orchestration
- allow new products to be added without modifying the platform core.

---

# 3. Architectural Principles

The backend follows five guiding principles.

## 3.1 API First

Everything communicates through well-defined APIs.

---

## 3.2 Product Isolation

Every product owns only its own business logic.

Example:

Chess2Fight knows nothing about Song2Dance.

Song2Dance knows nothing about Chess.

---

## 3.3 Shared Platform

Authentication, uploads, jobs, orchestration and storage are platform capabilities shared by every product.

---

## 3.4 HXT as the Universal Language

No renderer communicates directly with product analyzers.

Every product generates HXT.

Every renderer consumes HXT.

---

## 3.5 Asynchronous by Default

Long-running operations never block API requests.

Uploads always return immediately.

Background workers perform processing.

